In 2015, the [[UK Government]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-rolls-out-flagship-degree-apprenticeships|title=Government rolls-out flagship Degree Apprenticeships - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/degree-apprenticeships-are-quietly-revolutionising-higher-education|title=Degree apprenticeships are quietly revolutionising higher education|date=2018-04-01|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2018-04-03|language=en}}</ref> rolled out the '''degree apprenticeship''' programme which was developed as part of the [[apprenticeship#United Kingdom|higher apprenticeship]] standard. The programme is the equivalent of a [[Master's degree|masters]] or [[Bachelor's degree|bachelor's]] degree which offers a level 6 – 7 qualification.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/mar/06/from-barclays-to-boots-apprenticeships-are-transforming-management-training|title=From Barclays to Boots, apprenticeships are transforming management training|last=Doughty|first=Richard|date=2018-03-06|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-03}}</ref> Training for this qualification includes working in a full-time job as well as studying at a partner University or training provider.
== Requirements == Degree apprenticeships have been designed for learners 18 years of age or older.
Candidates interested in this programme must already have a level-3 qualification such as an advanced [[apprenticeship]], A [[A-Levels|levels]] or an International [[International Baccalaureate|Baccalaureat]]. However, some programmes may require further training.
