{{About|the common term "real life"|things named "Real Life"|Real Life (disambiguation){{!}}Real Life}}
'''"Real life"''' is a phrase used originally in literature to distinguish between the '''real world''' and fictional or idealized worlds, and in [[acting]] to distinguish between performers and the characters they portray. More recently, it has become a popular term on the [[Internet]] to describe events, people, activities, and interactions occurring offline; or otherwise not primarily through the medium of the Internet. It is also used as a metaphor to distinguish life in a vocational setting as opposed to an academic one.
==As distinct from fiction== [[File:BlakeStories1 (cropped).png|thumb|upright|Illustration by [[William Blake]] for Wollstonecraft's ''Original Stories'' (1791)]] When used to distinguish from fictional worlds or [[fictional universe|universe]]s against the [[consensus reality]] of the reader, the term has a long history: {{quote|Authors, as a rule, attempt to select and portray types rarely met with in their entirety, but these types are nevertheless more real than real life itself.|[[Fyodor Dostoyevsky]]|''[[The Idiot (novel)|The Idiot]]''<ref name=Dostoyevsky>{{cite web |title=Fyodor Dostoyevsky: The Idiot: Part IV: Chapter I |work=The Free Online Library |url= http://dostoyevsky.thefreelibrary.com/The-Idiot/4-1#real+life |accessdate=2006-05-06}}</ref>}}
In her 1788 work, ''[[Original Stories from Real Life; with Conversations Calculated to Regulate the Affections, and Form the Mind to Truth and Goodness]]'', author [[Mary Wollstonecraft]] employs the term in her title, representing the work's focus on a middle-class ethos which she viewed as superior to the court culture represented by [[fairy tales]] and the values of chance and [[luck]] found in [[chapbook]] stories for the poor.<ref>Wollstonecraft, Mary. Original Stories from Real Life. London: Printed for Joseph Johnson, 1788. Available from Eighteenth Century Collections Online. (by subscription only) Retrieved on 13 October 2007.</ref> As phrased by Gary Kelly, writing about the work, "The phrase ‘real life’ strengthens ‘original’, excluding both the artificial and the fictional or imaginary."<ref>Kelly, Gary. ''Revolutionary Feminism: The Mind and Career of Mary Wollstonecraft''. London: Macmillan, 1992. {{ISBN|0-312-12904-1}}.</ref>
Similarly, the phrase can be used to distinguish an [[actor]] from a character, e.g. "In real life, he has a British accent" or "In real life, he lives in Los Angeles."
There is a related but slightly distinct usage among [[live action role playing|role-players]] and [[historical reenactment|historical reenactors]], to distinguish the fantasy or historical context from the actual world and the role-player or actor from the character, e.g. "What do you do in real life?" or "Where do you live in real life?"
== As distinct from the Internet == On the Internet, "real life" refers to life [[Online and offline|offline]]. Online, the [[initialism]] "IRL" stands for "in real life", with the meaning "not on the Internet".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acronymfinder.com/af-query.asp?String=exact&Acronym=IRL|title=AcronymFinder.com search for IRL}}</ref> For example, while Internet users may speak of having "met" someone that they have contacted via [[online chat]] or in an [[online game|online gaming]] context, to say that they met someone "in real life" is to say that they literally encountered them at a physical location. Some, arguing that the Internet is part of real life, prefer to use "away from the keyboard" ([[wikt:AFK|AFK]]), e.g. the documentary ''[[TPB AFK]]''.
Some [[Sociology|sociologists]] engaged in the study of the Internet have predicted that someday, a distinction between online and offline worlds may seem "quaint", noting that certain types of online activity, such as sexual intrigues, have already made a full transition to complete legitimacy and "reality".<ref name="Slater">{{cite book|title=Handbook of New Media: Social Shaping and Consequences of ICTs|date=2002|publisher=Sage Publications Inc|isbn=0-7619-6510-6|pages=533–543|chapter=Social Relationships and Identity On-line and Off-line|editor=Leah Lievrouw and Sonia Livingstone|author=Don Slater}}</ref>
===Related terminology===
The [[initialism]] "RL" stands for "real life" and "IRL" for "in real life." For example, one can speak of "meeting IRL" someone whom one has met online, such as in "LMIRL" ("let's meet in real life"). It may also be used to express an inability to use the Internet for a time due to "RL problems". Some internet users use the [[idiom]]s "[[face time]]", "meatspace", or "meat world", which contrast with the term "[[cyberspace]]".<ref name="WordSpy">{{cite web|url=http://www.wordspy.com/words/meatspace.asp|title=meatspace (MEET.spays) n.|date=1996-11-14|publisher=Paul McFedries and Logophilia Limited|accessdate=2008-08-11|work=Word Spy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thephoenix.com/article_ektid17440.aspx|title=Does your life suck?|last=Dodero|first=Camille|date=17 July 2006|publisher=''[[The Phoenix (magazine)|The Phoenix]]''|quote=Beyond this world, in real life — a/k/a what Second Lifers refer to as "meatspace," where your body is made of flesh, not bytes…|accessdate=2007-07-23}}</ref> "Meatspace" has appeared in the ''[[Financial Times]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/d0f71fb6-3243-11db-ab06-0000779e2340,dwp_uuid=4e612cca-6707-11da-a650-0000779e2340,print=yes.html|title=Warning: interruption overload|date=2006-08-23|publisher=Ft.com|author=Rhymer Rigby|accessdate=2011-10-22|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813224049/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/d0f71fb6-3243-11db-ab06-0000779e2340,dwp_uuid=4e612cca-6707-11da-a650-0000779e2340,print=yes.html|archivedate=13 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and in [[science fiction]] literature.<ref>For example: * {{cite book|title=Cryptonomicon|last=Stephenson|first=Neal|publisher=HarperCollins|year=2000|isbn=0-380-78862-4|page=529|quote=Current meatspace coordinates, hot from the GPS receiver card in my laptop: ...}} * {{cite book|title=T2: Rising Storm|last=Stirling|first=S. M.|publisher=HarperCollins|year=2003|isbn=0-380-80817-X|series=T2 Series|page=53|quote=On the Internet the gloves come off and people say things they'd ''never'' say in meat space.}} </ref> Some early uses of the term include a post to the [[Usenet newsgroup]] austin.public-net in 1993<ref>{{cite web|url=http://groups.google.com/group/austin.public-net/browse_thread/thread/ab22c492a3319c44/798af58d879feba0?q=meatspace&_done=%2Fgroups%3Fq%3Dmeatspace%26start%3D0%26scoring%3Dd%26num%3D100%26hl%3Den%26ie%3DUTF-8%26lr%3D%26as_qdr%3D%26as_drrb%3Db%26as_mind%3D31%26as_minm%3D1%26as_miny%3D1981%26as_maxd%3D2%26as_maxm%3D3%26as_maxy%3D1996%26safe%3Doff%26&_doneTitle=Back+to+Search&&d#798af58d879feba0|title=Austin CyberSpace Journal #1|last=Barnes|first=Douglas|date=21 February 1993|quote=Meatspace update (quick rundown on where/how to interact with net.folks in meatspace, i.e., regular events, social gatherings, restaurant hangouts, etc.)|accessdate=2008-03-13}}</ref> and an article in ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' about [[John Perry Barlow]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.seattletimes.nwsource.com/cgi-bin/texis.cgi/web/vortex/display?slug=2149736&date=19951030&query=meatspace|title=He's Trying To Build A Community On-Line -- Grateful Dead Lyricist Ventures Into Cyberspace|last=Andrews|first=Paul|date=30 October 1995|work=The Seattle Times|quote=John Perry Barlow is multitasking between cyberspace, meatspace and parentspace about as well as a mere mortal can do.|accessdate=2008-03-13}}</ref> The term entered the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=36770|title='Lookist' Britain: the way we look inspires the new English|accessdate=2008-03-13}}</ref>
==As distinct from the academic world== The phrase is also used to distinguish [[academia|academic life]] from work in other sectors, in a manner similar to the term "real world". A person with experience in "real life" or the "real world" has experience beyond book-learning. It may also be used, often pejoratively, to distinguish other insular [[Subculture|subcultures]], work environments, or [[Lifestyle (sociology)|lifestyles]] from more traditional social and professional activities. The terms "real life" and "the real world" may also be used to describe [[adulthood]] and the adult world as distinct from [[childhood]] and [[adolescence]].
